k.com/redirect/58f96c68-5968-4b18-8d6d-1703adfa8304?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the =E2=80=9CFinancial Innov=
ation and Technology for the 21st=C2=A0Century Act,=E2=80=9D in a watershed=
 moment for the U.S. digital asset ecosystem. FIT21 provides the robust, ti=
me-tested consumer protections and regulatory certainty necessary to allow =
digital asset innovation to flourish in the United States.
Packy here. It=E2=80=99s been a big week for crypto in the nation=E2=80=99s=
 capitol, the result of the hard and patient work of a lot of people in edu=
cating policymakers on the industry.=20
On Wednesday, the House of Representatives passed the Financial Innovation =
for the 21st Century Act (FIT21). The bill provides much-needed regulatory =
clarity for the crypto industry, and pushes crypto out of the weird gray ar=
ea it=E2=80=99s been forced to operate in. Entrepreneurs trying to build ne=
w things should understand the rules of the road going in, and FIT21 is a s=
tep in that direction. There=E2=80=99s still a long way to go =E2=80=94 it =
will face headwinds in the Senate =E2=80=94 but it=E2=80=99s the second tim=
e in two weeks where crypto received bipartisan support from the House. 71 =
Democrats, including financial whiz kid Nancy Pelosi, voted for the bill. C=
rypto is becoming bipartisan.=20
Then yesterday, a double whammy!=20
First, the SEC approved an Ethereum ETF. More than a financial win, as a16z=
 crypto General Counsel and all around good guy Miles Jennings tweeted [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/2614fe76-6ec7-429c-973b-ea29b204b528?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CThese =
approvals enshrine the SEC=E2=80=99s position in 2018 - ETH is not a securi=
ty. That means the SEC has formally recognized that decentralization moves =
tokens outside of the US securities law regime. With that beachhead establi=
shed, all projects now have a path forward.=E2=80=9D=20
Then, the House came back for more, passing Tom Emmer=E2=80=99s CBDC Anti-S=
urveillance State Act, banning the Fed from issuing a Central Bank Digital =
Currency. This is great, because as North Carolina Rep. Patrick McHenry exp=
lained [ https://substack.com/redirect/4491105b-365b-4d04-b519-ed695f71fc4c=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=
=80=9CIf not open, permissionless, and private, a CBDC is no more than a CC=
P-style surveillance tool waiting to be weaponized.=E2=80=9D=20
As I wrote this week [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb7c0c56-3351-4b27-bae=
1-9391f9135c4b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ], crypto provides the best set of tools we have to address challeng=
es with money and finance, and to make capitalism more efficient [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/79c289b8-b062-499c-9e58-378bdf05e0fc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. It=E2=80=99s been hel=
d back, in part, by murky regulation and overzealous regulators. Congress=
=E2=80=99 about-face on crypto this week is a big step towards unleashing e=
ntrepreneurial talent on making sure the whole financial system runs more s=
moothly. It=E2=80=99s time to BUIDL.=20
We love to see a little pro-innovation lawmaking heading into Memorial Day =
Weekend. What a country.=20
(2) Mapping the Mind of a Large Language Model [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/ffa27d4c-daa5-420a-a200-9facb89a5e09?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Anthropic
Today we report a significant advance in understanding the inner workings o=
f AI models. We have identified how millions of concepts are represented in=
side Claude Sonnet, one of our deployed large language models. This is the =
first ever detailed look inside a modern, production-grade large language m=
odel. This interpretability discovery could, in future, help us make AI mod=
els safer.
Researchers at Anthropic made an interpretability breakthrough, giving us a=
n inside look at how these large language models really work. LLMs work by =
representing concepts through patterns of neuron activations, where each co=
ncept is spread across many neurons, and each neuron contributes to multipl=
e concepts. This allows the model to understand and generate responses base=
d on these internal representations. Anthropic=E2=80=99s work, for the firs=
t time, gives us a better mapping of these internal concept representations=
=2E
As an example, Anthropic's research showed that amplifying the "Golden Gate=
 Bridge" feature in the model made it obsessively mention the bridge, even =
in unrelated contexts. This demonstrated that specific features control beh=
avior.
Importantly, identifying the controllable features of a model will mean tha=
t LLM builders will be able to influence the model=E2=80=99s behavior. Know=
ing how the model works means the models can be better monitored, steered, =
and put to good use doing things for us humans.=20
Want to see what it means for yourself? The Anthropic team pushed a Golden =
Gate Bridge Mode. =E2=80=9CWe found a feature that, when amplified, can mak=
e Claude focus intensely on the Golden Gate Bridge. For a limited time, you=
 can talk with this version of the model.=E2=80=9D=20
It=E2=80=99s fun. Go play with it =E2=80=94 click the little Golden Gate Br=
idge icon on the right [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee419775-9e6e-4f1a-a=
44d-73f00baf39aa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=94 and see for yourself that we=E2=80=99re going to be in=
 control of this technology, not the other way around.=20
No need to Pause, just to understand. Who woulda thunk it?=20
(3) A Vast, Untapped Source of Lithium Has Just Been Found in The US [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/0569ff05-17e2-4e27-b95b-988383f74203?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Carly Cassella for Science Alert
Over vast stretches of time, deep groundwater has dissolved the lithium in =
these rocks, essentially "mining the subsurface", according [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/0430c7be-4d0e-452c-871d-ee09b325cf14?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to Justin Mackey, a researc=
her at the National Energy Technology Laboratory in Pennsylvania. Mackey an=
d his colleagues have now found that when wastewater is dredged up from the=
 deep by fracking activities, it contains an astonishing amount of lithium.
Packy again, back with maybe my favorite theme: people keep saying we=E2=80=
=99re running out of a particular resource, or that we can=E2=80=99t mine t=
hem profitably or cleanly, and then we just go ahead and discover boatloads=
 of that resource right in our backyard! God bless America =F0=9F=87=BA=F0=
=9F=87=B8
This time, it=E2=80=99s lithium, the element we need to make all of the bat=
teries we=E2=80=99re going to need to make to electrify our vehicles and st=
abilize our grid [ https://substack.com/redirect/71831487-208c-4ecb-99d7-db=
1c5c3608b6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]. Currently, there=E2=80=99s just one large lithium mine in the US - we=
=E2=80=99re net importers. The Department of Energy wants to produce all of=
 our own lithium domestically [ https://substack.com/redirect/b298972d-068d=
-4e66-9009-c2189a863298?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], but lithium mining is controversial for its environmenta=
l impact.
Then last year, as we covered in Weekly Dose #60, researchers discovered wh=
at may be the world=E2=80=99s largest lithium deposit in an ancient supervo=
lcano at McDermitt caldera.=20
Now, we=E2=80=99ve struck Lithium again, in my home state of Pennsylvania, =
in the most beautiful way possible.=20
Pennsylvania is home to the Marcellus Shale, a massive source of natural ga=
s from fracking. Injecting high-pressure fluid into shale formations create=
s fractures =E2=80=94 hence fracking =E2=80=94 which frees up oil and gas. =
Just when we thought we were reaching peak oil, humans figured out fracking=
, and unlocked a huge source of hydrocarbons on our home turf. Fracking is =
controversial, but it=E2=80=99s awesome.=20
And now it=E2=80=99s even more awesome. Turns out, deep groundwater has dis=
solved lithium in the rocks over millennia, and when we dredge up the waste=
water from fracking, it contains massive amounts of lithium! The study, pub=
lished in Science Reports [ https://substack.com/redirect/acd631cf-2242-440=
1-a843-02c2483e793c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ], estimated just how much lithium is in that wastewater, and t=
here=E2=80=99s a lot.=20
Extracting even a conservative amount of lithium from the Marcellus wastewa=
ter could meet 30% of current US lithium demand.=20
That=E2=80=99s fracking poetic.=20
(4) Element from the periodic table=E2=80=99s far reaches coaxed into elusi=
ve compound [ https://substack.com/redirect/2cf490ed-b1d4-4030-b2c2-665bd92=
25b64?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Mark Peplow for Nature
Chemists achieve synthetic feat with radioactive promethium for the first t=
ime.
A team at Oak Ridge National Laboratory synthesized the first chemical comp=
lex with radioactive promethium, an elusive element in the periodic table. =
The work exposes promethium's bonding behavior with other atoms in water, b=
ridging what has long been a crucial gap in chemistry knowledge. So what=E2=
=80=99s promethium and why do we care?
Promethium is a rare radioactive element from the lanthanide series, found =
in nuclear waste. It=E2=80=99s currently used in products like pacemakers a=
nd spacecraft power sources. The new research gives us a better understandi=
ng of how promethium bonds to other elements, and thus, gives us a better u=
nderstanding of how we can extract promethium from those other elements =E2=
=80=94 for example, separating promethium from similar elements in nuclear =
waste. Beyond better nuclear waste management, the promethium learnings cou=
ld lead to more efficient methods for separating and purifying other rare-e=
arth elements, enhancing the production of high-tech products like lasers, =
magnets, and batteries.
(5) Javier Milei=E2=80=99s Radical Plan to Transform Argentina [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/f2154191-c8fb-4bb1-a0a6-327c771436d5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Vera Bergengruen for Time
We don=E2=80=99t really have a perro in this fight, but thought it was wort=
h sharing this new Time profile of Argentinian President Javier Milei. Mile=
i certainly has his critics and it's frankly is too early to tell if his ec=
onomic plans will pan out for Argentina in the long run, but the guy is doi=
ng what he promised to do and the early results speak for themself. Inflati=
on is down. The currency is devalued by 50%.  Spending is down. Argentina r=
an a surplus in Q1 =E2=80=9824, the country's first quarterly surplus since=
 2008.=C2=A0Milei is delivering on his plan, whether you or the Argentinian=
 people want him to. Milei promised change, and change is what he is delive=
ring.
Whether you agree with or like Milei is besides the point. The point is tha=
t real change is possible within democratic governments, and that change ca=
n (and in many cases should!) happen quickly.
On this Memorial Day Weekend, the story of Argentina serves as a good remin=
der. In the early 20th century, it was one of the top 10 wealthiest countri=
es in the world and experienced long periods of political stability. Today =
it=E2=80=99s the ~75th richest country in the world. What happened? To over=
generalize: socialism and mismanagement.=20
Capitalism and democracy are worth fighting for. We=E2=80=99re thankful tha=
t generations of American men and women, much braver than me, agree with th=
at statement and have paid the highest price protecting those ideals.
Enjoy the long weekend, support the troops, and God Bless America.
If you miss us too much this weekend and you haven=E2=80=99t read it yet, g=
o read Better Tools, Bigger Companies [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb7c0=
c56-3351-4b27-bae1-9391f9135c4b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

